    widgets you just used.
  </p>

  <h2>Self-test</h2>

  <ol class="my-6 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      In the QFTVisualizer, set the input to a single basis state
      (any of the <code>|xxxx⟩</code> presets). What's the output
      probability distribution? Why does the QFT of a single basis
      state always have uniform <em>magnitude</em>? (Hint: look at
      the formula above — the phase rotates but the magnitude
      <code>|1/√N|</code> is constant.)
    </li>
    <li>
      In the period-finding widget, set <code>N = 15, a = 4</code>.
      Why does the sequence collapse so quickly? Where would a
      4-qubit QFT peak if you ran this function through Shor?
    </li>
    <li>
      The period-finding widget refuses <code>a</code> values that
      aren't coprime with <code>N</code>. Why is that a precondition
      of Shor's algorithm — what would go wrong in the quantum
      subroutine if <code>gcd(a, N) ≠ 1</code>? (Hint: think about
      what <code>a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code> looks like when it shares
      a factor with <code>N</code>.)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <MathNerds title="Why the QFT peaks at multiples of Q/r">
    <p>
      Let <code>r</code> be the period of
      <code>f(x) = a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code> and let
      <code>Q = 2<sup>n</sup></code> be the register size. Suppose
      <code>r</code> divides <code>Q</code> evenly. Prepare the
      quantum register in the uniform superposition over the indices
      where <code>f</code> hits some value <code>y</code>:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="|\psi_y\rangle \;=\; \sqrt{\frac{r}{Q}}\,\sum_{j=0}^{Q/r - 1}\, |x_0 + j r\rangle" />
    <p>
      where <code>x_0</code> is the smallest <code>x</code> with
      <code>f(x_0) = y</code>. Apply the QFT:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="F|\psi_y\rangle \;=\; \frac{1}{\sqrt{r}}\,\sum_{j=0}^{r-1}\, e^{2\pi i\, x_0\, j Q/(r Q)} \, |jQ/r\rangle" />
    <p>
      Every output amplitude away from a multiple of
      <code>Q/r</code> cancels — a geometric series in
      <code>e<sup>2πi/r</sup></code> sums to zero unless its phase is
      stationary. The surviving amplitudes sit at <code>k = jQ/r</code>
      for <code>j = 0, 1, …, r−1</code>, each with probability
      <code>1/r</code>. That's the comb pattern the period-4 preset
      paints in QFTVisualizer.
    </p>
    <p>
      When <code>r</code> does <em>not</em> divide <code>Q</code> the
      peaks blur into nearby bins, but they still concentrate near
      the same <code>jQ/r</code> values; the continued-fractions
      algorithm recovers <code>r</code> from a measured bin with
      high probability. The peak-hint panel in PeriodFinding shows
      the rounded predictions when divisibility fails.
    </p>
  </MathNerds>

